needs a proper notion of intrinsic boundary. We say that geodesics
in $(X,d)$ can be \emph{locally extended} if for all geodesics $\gamma:[0,1]\to X$
there is a local geodesic $\tilde{\gamma}:[-\epsilon,1]\to X$ agreeing
on $[0,1]$ with $\gamma$. In the smooth setting, $x\in\partial M$
would imply that there is a geodesic starting at $x$ such that $-\dot{\gamma}_{x}\ne T_{x}M$.
In particular, $\gamma$ cannot be extended beyond $x$. 
\begin{defn}
[geodesic boundary] The \emph{geodesic boundary} $\partial_{g}C$
of subset $C\subset X$ is the set of all $x\in C$ such that there
is a geodesic in $C$ that cannot be locally extended in $C$.\end{defn}
\begin{rem*}
The notion differs from the boundary of Alexandrov spaces. Indeed,
if the singular set is dense then the geodesic boundary is dense as
well. 
\end{rem*}
